===Etymology===
Area word (rice culture originated in the south). Often compared with {{cog|hmx-pro|*mbləu||rice plant/paddy}}, whence {{cog|mww|nplej}} ({{zh-ref|Bodman, 1980}}).

The relationship with similar-looking Mon-Khmer words is ambiguous ({{zh-ref|Schuessler, 2007}}). {{zh-ref|Ferlus (2010)}} proposes a connection to {{cog|aav-pro|*srɔ(ː)ʔ||paddy}} (Sidwell's 2024 reconstruction; revised from Shorto's 2006 *''sruʔ''), which in turn is linked to {{cog|aav-pro|*sroʔ||taro}} (Sidwell's 2024 reconstruction; revised from Shorto's 2006 *''t₂rawʔ''), as the two plants share the same farming niche.

Alternatively, {{zh-ref|Sagart (2011)}} derives this word from {{och-l|舀|to scoop (hulled grain) from a mortar}}. If so, since the {{cog|hmx}} comparandum only has the derived sense of “rice”, it would be borrowed from Chinese rather than the other way around.

The native Min word {{zh-l|*粙}} may be a variant ({{zh-ref|Schuessler, 2007}}, ''apud'' {{w|Jerry Norman (sinologist)|Norman}}, [[p.c.]]).

